<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	We entered into a tax indemnification agreement with our existing shareholders prior to the IPO and could become obligated to make payments to them for any additional federal, state or local income taxes assessed against them for fiscal periods prior to the completion of our IPO.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We have historically been treated as an &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation for U.S. federal income tax purposes. Concurrent with and as a result of our IPO, our &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation status terminated and we are currently subject to federal income taxes and state income taxes. In the event of an adjustment to our reported taxable income for a period or periods prior to termination of our &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation status, our shareholders during those periods could be liable for additional income taxes for those prior periods. Therefore, prior to the consummation of our IPO, we entered into a tax indemnification agreement with the then-existing shareholders. Pursuant to the tax indemnification agreement, we agreed to indemnify and hold harmless each such shareholder on an after-tax basis against additional income taxes, plus interest and penalties, resulting from adjustments made, as a result of a final determination made by a competent tax authority, to the taxable income we reported as an &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation. Such indemnification will also include any reasonable and documented out-of-pocket expenses arising out of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	a claim for such tax liability.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Unseasonal or severe weather conditions may adversely affect our merchandise sales.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our business is adversely affected by unseasonal weather conditions. Sales of certain seasonal apparel items, especially outerwear, are dependent in part on the weather and may decline in years in which weather conditions do not favor the use of these products. Sales of our spring and summer products, which traditionally consist of lighter weight clothing, are adversely affected by cool or wet weather. Similarly, sales of our fall and winter products, which are traditionally weighted toward outerwear, are adversely affected by mild, dry or warm weather. Severe weather events may impact our ability to supply our retail stores, deliver orders to customers on schedule and staff our retail stores, fulfillment centers and call center, which could have an adverse effect on our busi
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ness and results of operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	We may be subject to assessments for additional taxes, including sales taxes, which could adversely affect our business.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In accordance with current law, we pay, collect and/or remit taxes in those states where we or our subsidiary, as applicable, maintain a physical presence. While we believe that we have appropriately remitted all taxes based on our interpretation of applicable law, tax laws are complex and their application differs from state to state. It is possible that some taxing jurisdictions may attempt to assess additional taxes and penalties on us or assert either an error in our calculation, a change in the application of law or an interpretation of the law that differs from our own, which may, if successful, adversely affect our busi
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ness and results of operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Several proposals have been made at the state and local level that would impose additional taxes on the sale of goods and services through the Internet. These proposals, if adopted, could substantially impair the growth of e-commerce and could diminish our opportunity to derive financi
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	al benefit from our activities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In conjunction with the &#x201C;Streamlined Sales Tax Project,&#x201D; an ongoing, multi-year effort by certain state and local governments to require collection and remittance of distant sales tax by out-of-state sellers, bills have been introduced in the U.S. Congress to overturn the U.S. Supreme Court&#x2019;s decision in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Quill Corp. v. North Dakota,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	540 U.S. 298 (1992), which limits the ability of state governments to require sellers outside of their own state to collect and remit sales taxes on goods purchased by in-state residents. An overturning of this decision may harm our customers and our business.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	We may become involved in a number of legal proceedings and audits, and outcomes of such legal proceedings and audits could adversely affect our business, financial condition and results of operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our business requires compliance with many laws and regulations, including labor and employment, customs, truth-in-advertising, consumer protection and zoning and occupancy laws and ordinances that regulate retailers generally and/or govern the importation, promotion and sale of merchandise and the operation of stores and warehouse facilities. Failure to achieve compliance could subject us to lawsuits and other proceedings, and could also lead to damage awards, fines and penalties. We may become involved in a number of legal proceedings and audits including government and agency investigations, and consumer, employment, tort and other litigation. We cannot predict with certainty the outcomes of these legal proceedings and other contingencies. The outcome of some of these legal proceedings, audits and other contingencies could require us to take, or refrain from taking, actions which could negatively affect our operations or require us to pay substantial amounts of money adversely affecting our financial condition and results of operations. Additionally, defending against these lawsuits and proceedings may be necessary, which could result in substantial costs and diversion of management&#x2019;s attention and resources, causing a material adverse effect on our business, financial condition and results of operations. There can be no assurance that any pending or future legal proceedings and audits will not have a material adverse effect on our business, financial condi
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	tion and results of operations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>

</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;">
	Changes to accounting rules or regulations could significantly affect our financial results.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Our consolidated financial statements are prepared in accordance with U.S. GAAP. New accounting rules or regulations and changes to existing accounting rules or regulations have occurred and may occur in the future. Future changes to accounting rules or regulations could negatively affect our results of operations and financial condition thro
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	ugh increased compliance costs.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	Risks Related to Ownership of our Class&nbsp;B Common Stock
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;">
	The dual class structure of our common stock and the existing ownership of common stock by our executive officers, directors and their affiliates have the effect of concentrating voting control with our executive officers, directors and their affiliates for the foreseeable future, which will limit your ability to influence corporate matters.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Our Class&nbsp;A common stock has ten votes per share, and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	our Class&nbsp;B common stock
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	has one vote per share. Given the greater number of votes per share attributed to our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Class&nbsp;A common stock, our Executive Chairman, Stephen L. Schlecht, who is our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	only Class&nbsp;A shareholder,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	beneficially own shares representing approximately 67.8% of the voting power of our outstanding capital stock. As a result of our dual class ownership structure, Mr. Schlecht will be able to exert a significant degree of influence or actual control over our management and affairs and over matters requiring shareholder approval, including the election of directors, a merger, consolidation or sale of all or substantially all of our assets and any other significant transaction. Furthermore, Mr.&nbsp;Schlecht will continue to exert a significant degree of influence or actual control over matters requiring shareholder approval, even if he owns
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	a number of Class A shares representing
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	as few as approximately 10% of the outstanding shares of our capital stock. Further, Mr. Schlecht owns shares representing approximately&nbsp;37.6% of the economic interest of our outstanding capital stock and, together with our other executive officers, directors and their affiliates, owns shares representing approximately 45.9% of the economic interest and 72.1% of the voting power of our outstanding capital stock. This concentrated control will limit your ability to influence corporate matters for the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	foreseeable future. For example, these shareholders will be able to control elections of directors, amendments of our articles of incorporation or bylaws, increases to the number of shares available for issuance under our equity incentive plans or adoption of new equity incentive plans and approval of any merger or sale of assets for the foreseeable future. This control may materially adversely affect the market price of our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Class&nbsp;B common stock.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Additionally, the holder
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	of our Class&nbsp;A common stock may cause us to make strategic decisions or pursue acquisitions that could involve risks to you or may not be aligned
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	with your interests. The holder
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	of our Class&nbsp;A common stock will also be
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 8PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	24
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">

</FONT>

	ts, including the requirements:

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Although we intend to have a majority of independent directors on our board even though we will be a controlled company, there is no guarantee that we will not take advantage of this exemption in the future. Accordingly, as long as we are a controlled company, holders of our Class&nbsp;B common stock may not have the same protections afforded to shareholders of companies that are subject to all of the NASDAQ cor
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	porate governance requirements.

<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;">
	Future sales of shares by existing shareholders could cause our stock price to decline.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Future sales of substantial amounts of shares of our Class&nbsp;B common stock in the public market could cause the prevailing market price for our Class B common stock to fall or impair our ability to raise equity capital in the future. Based on the number of shares out
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	standing as of January 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	, we had
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	28,951,742 shares
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	of Class B common stock outstanding. Of these outstanding shares
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	, 7,545,509
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	shares of Class B common stock sold by us in the IPO are freely tradable in the public market without restriction
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	or further registration under the Securities Act, and 19,49

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	3,452

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	shares of Class B common stock held by our affiliates, as that term is defined in Rule 144 under the Securities Act, may only be sold in compliance with the limitations described below.

	The

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	remaining

	shares

	of Class B common stock outstanding are deemed restricted because of securities laws or lock-up agreements. Of

	these 21,40

<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	In addition, stock markets have experienced extreme price and volume fluctuations that have affected and continue to affect the market prices of equity securities of many retail and e-commerce companies. Stock prices of many retail companies and e-commerce companies have fluctuated in a manner unrelated or disproportionate to the operating performance of those companies. In the past, shareholders have instituted securities class action litigation following periods of market volatility. If we were to become involved in securities litigation, it could subject us to substantial costs, divert resources and the attention of management from our business and materially adversely affect our business, financial c
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	ondition and operating results.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;">
	If securities or industry analysts do not publish research or reports about our business, or publish negative reports about our business, our share price and trading volume could decline.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	The trading market for our Class&nbsp;B common stock will depend in part on the research and reports that securities or industry analysts publish about us or our business, our market and our competitors. We do not have any control over these analysts. If one or more of the analysts who cover us downgrade our shares or change their opinion of our shares, our share price would likely decline. If one or more of these analysts cease coverage of our company or fail to regularly publish reports on us, we could lose visibility in the financial markets, which could cause our share pric
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	e or trading volume to decline.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;">
	We are an &#x201C;emerging growth company,&#x201D; and we cannot be certain if the reduced disclosure and exemption from the auditor attestation requirements applicable to &#x201C;emerging growth companies&#x201D; will make our Class&nbsp;B common stock less attractive to investors.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	We are an &#x201C;emerging growth company,&#x201D; as defined in the JOBS Act, and we intend to take advantage of certain exemptions from various reduced regulatory and reporting requirements that are otherwise generally applicable to other public companies. As an emerging growth company: (i)&nbsp;we are exempt from the requirement to obtain an audit of our internal control over financial reporting pursuant to the Sarbanes-Oxley Act; (ii)&nbsp;we are permitted to provide less extensive disclosure about our executive compensation arrangements; and (iii)&nbsp;we are not required to hold non-binding advisory votes on executive compensation
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	or golden parachute provisions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	We remain an emerging growth company and may continue to take advantage of these provisions until the earliest to occur of: (i)&nbsp;the last day of our fiscal year following the fifth anniversary of our IPO, which anniversary will occur on the last day of fiscal 2020; (ii)&nbsp;the date on which we are deemed to be a &#x201C;large accelerated filer&#x201D; (which means (a)&nbsp;the market value of our common stock that is held by non-affiliates exceeds $700&nbsp;million as of the last business day of our most recently completed second fiscal quarter, (b)&nbsp;we have filed at least one annual report on Form 10-K, and (c)&nbsp;we have been subject to the reporting requirements of the Exchange Act for at least twelve months); (iii)&nbsp;the last day of our fiscal year during which our annual gross revenue exceeds $1.0&nbsp;billion; and (iv)&nbsp;the date on which we issue more than $1.0&nbsp;billion of non-convertible debt during
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	the previous three-year period.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	We cannot predict if investors will find our Class&nbsp;B common stock less attractive or our company less comparable to certain other public companies because we will rely on these exemptions. If some investors find our Class&nbsp;B common stock less attractive as a result of our reliance on these exemptions, there may be a less active trading market for our Class&nbsp;B common stock, and our stock price may be more volatile. We also cannot predict if the failure to seek independent auditor attesta
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	tion of our internal control
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	over financial reporting pursuant to Section&nbsp;404 will cause certain inadequacies or weaknesses in our inte
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	rnal controls to go undetected.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;">
	The requirements of being a public company may strain our resources, divert management&#x2019;s attention and affect our ability to attract and retain additional executive management and qualified board members.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	As a public company, we are subject to the reporting requirements of the Exchange Act, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, the Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, the listing requirements of the NASDAQ Global Select Market and other applicable securities rules and regulations. Compliance with these rules and regulations will increase our legal and financial compliance costs, make some activities more difficult, time-consuming or costly and increase demand on our systems and resources, particularly after we are no longer an &#x201C;emerging growth company.&#x201D; The Exchange Act requires, among other things, that we file annual, quarterly and current reports with respect to our business and results of operations. The Sarbanes-Oxley Act requires, among other things, that we maintain effective disclosure controls and procedures and internal control over
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 8PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	26
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>

<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage28"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#DLTH-20160131X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	financial reporting. In order to maintain and, if required, improve our disclosure controls and procedures and internal control over financial
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	reporting
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, significant resources and management oversight may be required. As a result, management&#x2019;s attention may be diverted from other business concerns, which could materially adversely affect our business and results of operations. We will need to hire additional employees or engage outside consultants to comply with these requirements, which will i
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ncrease our costs and expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In addition, changing laws, regulations and standards relating to corporate governance and public disclosure are creating uncertainty for public companies, increasing legal and financial compliance costs and making some activities more time-consuming. These laws, regulations and standards are subject to varying interpretations, in many cases due to their lack of specificity, and, as a result, their application in practice may evolve over time as new guidance is provided by regulatory and governing bodies. This could result in continuing uncertainty regarding compliance matters and higher costs necessitated by ongoing revisions to disclosure and governance practices. We intend to invest resources to comply with evolving laws, regulations and standards, and this investment may result in increased general and administrative expenses and a diversion of management&#x2019;s time and attention from revenue-generating activities to compliance activities. If our efforts to comply with new laws, regulations and standards differ from the activities intended by regulatory or governing bodies due to ambiguities related to their application and practice, regulatory authorities may initiate legal proceedings against us, and our business may be
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	materially adversely affected.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	As a result of disclosure o
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	f information in this annual report
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and in filings required of a public company, our business and financial condition will become more visible, which we believe may result in threatened or actual litigation, including by competitors and other third parties. If such claims are successful, our business and results of operations could be materially adversely affected, and even if the claims do not result in litigation or are resolved in our favor, these claims, and the time and resources necessary to resolve them, could divert the resources of our management and materially adversely affect our business, financial conditio
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	n and operating results.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	In connection with the preparation of our financial statements
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	for fiscal 2013 and fiscal 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	, we identified a material weakness in our internal control over financial reporting. Any failure to maintain effective internal control over our financial reporting could materially adversely affect us.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	In connection with the preparation of our fiscal 2013 and fiscal 2014 consolidated financial statements, we identified a material weakness in our internal control over financial reporting relating to period cutoffs impacting revenue recognition and inventory receipts. Our practice with respect to revenue recognition had been to recognize revenue upon shipment of the product (for direct sales) or at the point of sale (for retail store transactions). This had been our practice because we believed that these were the points when the following four revenue recognition criteria were met: (a)&nbsp;persuasive evidence of an arrangement exists; (b)&nbsp;title has passed to the customer; (c)&nbsp;the sales price is fixed and determinable and no further obligations exist; and (d)&nbsp;collectability is reasonably assured. Upon further evaluation of the revenue guidance, we concluded that the appropriate time to recognize revenue with respect to our direct sales is upon receipt by the customer in accordance with U.S. GAAP. Accordingly, we have changed our revenue recognition policy for our direct business to recognize revenue upon receipt by the customer.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	With respect to inventory receipts, we have certain suppliers for whom we had recognized inventory and accounts payable upon receipt of invoice and proof of shipment from the supplier. The actual term for these shipments was FOB Shipping Point, indicating that we should have recognized inventory and accounts payable at the time of shipment by the suppliers. We have revised our accounting policy to record these transactions at the time of shipment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Under standards established by the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board, a deficiency in internal control over financial reporting exists when the design or operation of a control does not allow management or personnel, in the normal course of performing their assigned functions, to prevent or detect misstatements on a timely basis. A material weakness is a deficiency or combination of deficiencies in internal control over financial reporting, such that there is a reasonable possibility that a material misstatement of our annual or interim financial statements will not be prevented or detected and corrected on a timely basis. We
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	have remediated
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	identified material weakness
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	as of January 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. Additional material weaknesses or significant deficiencies may be identified in the future. If we identify such issues or if we are unable to produce accurate and timely financial statements, our stock price may be adversely affected and we may be unable to maintain compliance with the NASDAQ Sto
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ck Market listing requirements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Anti-takeover provisions in our charter documents and under Wisconsin law could make an acquisition of our company more difficult, limit attempts by our shareholders to replace or remove our current management and limit the market price of our Class&nbsp;B common stock.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Provisions in our amended and restated articles of incorporation and amended and restated bylaws may have the effect of delaying or preventing a change of control or changes in our management. In addition to the dual class structure of our common stock, our amended and restated articles of incorporation and amended and restated
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	bylaws include provisions that:
</FONT>
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

In addition, because we are incorporated in Wisconsin, the Wisconsin control share acquisition statute and Wisconsin&#x2019;s &#x201C;business combination&#x201D; provisions would apply and limit the ability of an acquiring person to engage in certain transactions or to exercise full voting power of acquired shares under certain circumstances. As a result, offers to acquire us, which may represent a premium over the available market price of our Class&nbsp;B common stock, may be withdrawn or otherwise fail to be realized

<EFX_PROPERTIES>
<A NAME="FIS_PROPERTIES"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<TABLE CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:58.65PT;BORDER-TOP:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-LEFT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-BOTTOM:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;BORDER-RIGHT:1PT NONE #D9D9D9 ;HEIGHT:1.00PT;PADDING:0PT;">

	The following is a list of names and ages of executive officers of Duluth Trading indicating all positions and offices held by each such person and each such person&#x2019;s principal occupation(s) or employment during the past five years. There are no family relationships among these officers, nor any arrangement or understanding between any officer and any other person pursuant to w

	hich the officer was selected.

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	al amounts were distributed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	from
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	time to time to our shareholders at the discretion of the board of directors. During fiscal 2014
</FONT>

	, we paid distributions of $15.1 million to our shareholders. During fiscal 2015, we paid distributions
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$60
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.1
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million to our shareholders, which
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	included $46.3 milli

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	on for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	portion of the currently estimated final distribution of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$46.6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million (resulting from the termination of our &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation status) of 100% of the cumulative undistributed taxable earnings from the date of our for
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	mation through November 25, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. The final &#x201C;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	S&#x201D; corporation distribution
</FONT>

	include
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	s &nbsp;

	an amount
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of income based on our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	results of operations for the full 2015 calendar year, which is our 2015 tax year, prorated from January 1, 2015 through the date of our
</FONT>

</FONT>

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	Use of Proceeds from Public Offering of Class B Common Stock
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	On November
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	25, 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	we closed our IPO, in which we registered and sold 7,666,667 shares of Class B common stock at a price of $12.00 per share. The aggregate offering price for shares sold in the offering was approximately $92.0 million. The offer and sale of all of the shares in the IPO were registered
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	under the Securities Act pursuant to a registration statement on Form S-1 (File No. 333-207300), which was declared effective by the SEC on November 19, 2015.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We raised approximately $8
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million in net proceeds after deducting underwriting discounts and commissions of approximately $6.4 million and other offeri
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ng expenses of approximately $1.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We used $46.3 million of the net proceeds from the offering to pay in full a short term note previously borrowed from a bank to pay a portion of the distribution of 100% of the cumulative undis
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	tributed taxable earnings to our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	then existing s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	hareholders from the date of our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	formation throug
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	h the date of termination of our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation status.
</FONT>

	remaining $37.

	6

	million in net proceeds from the offering, there has been no material change in the planned use of proceeds from the Company&#x2019;s IPO as described in the final prospectus filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission pursuant to Rule 424(b)(4).

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT 1.1PT 1.1PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	MANAGEMENT&#x2019;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	The following discussion and analysis of the financial condition and results of operations should be read in conjunction with the consolidated financial statements and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	the accompanying notes and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	information contained in other sections inclu
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	ded elsewhere in this annual report
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	, particularly, &#x201C;Risk Factors,&#x201D; &#x201C;Selected Financial Data,&#x201D; and &#x201C;Business.&#x201D;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	This discussion and analysis is based on the beliefs of our management, as well as assumptions made by, and inf
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	ormation currently available to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	our management. The statements in this discussion and analysis concerning expectations regarding our future performance, liquidity and capital resources, as well as other non-historical statements in this discussion and analysis, are forward-looking statements. See &#x201C;Forward-Looking Statement
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#x201D;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	These forward-looking statements are subject to numerous risks and uncertainties, including those described under &#x201C;Risk Factors
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#x201D; Our actual results could differ materially from those suggested or implied by any forward-looking statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Effective February 2013, we changed our fiscal year end from December&nbsp;31 to the Sunday nearest to January&nbsp;31. The following discussion contains references to fiscal years 2015
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	, 2014 and 2013, which refer to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	our fiscal year
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	ended January 31, 2016, February&nbsp;1, 2015 and February&nbsp;2, 2014, respectively. Fiscal years 2015, 2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	and 2013 were 52-week periods.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	Overview
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We are a rapidly growing lifestyle brand of men&#x2019;s and women&#x2019;s casual wear, workwear and accessories sold exclusively through our own direct and retail channels. The direct segment, consisting of our website and catalogs, offers products nationwide and represented
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	87.6
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of our fiscal 2015 consolidated net sales. In 20
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	10, we added retail to our omni
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	channel platform with the opening of our first store. Since then, we expanded our retail presence
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, and as of January 31, 2016, we operated seven retail stores and two outlet stores. Net sales for our retail segment represented
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	12.4%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	of our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	fiscal 2015 consolidated net sales.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We offer a comprehensive line of innovative, durable and functional product
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, such as our Longtail T
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:5PT;TOP:-4PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;LINE-HEIGHT:100%">
	&#xAE;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shirts, Buck Naked
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:5PT;TOP:-4PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;LINE-HEIGHT:100%">
	TM
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	underwear, and Fire Hose
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:5PT;TOP:-4PT;POSITION:RELATIVE;LINE-HEIGHT:100%">
	&#xAE;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	work pants, which reflect our position as the Modern, Self-Reliant American Lifestyle brand. Our brand has a heritage in workwear that transcends tradesmen and appeals to a broad demographic f
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	or everyday and on-the-job use.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	From our heritage as a catalog for those working in the building trades, Duluth Trading has become a widely recognized brand and proprietary line of innovative and functional apparel and gear. Over the last decade, we have created strong brand awareness, built a loyal customer base and generated robust sales momentum. We have done so by sticking to our roots of &#x201C;there&#x2019;s gotta be a better way&#x201D; and through our relentless focus on providing our customers wi
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	th quality, functional products.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	A summary of our financial results is as follows:
</FONT>

	Our retail stores have achieved an average payback of less than two years.
</FONT>
</P>

</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	See &#x201C;Reconciliation of Net Income to Adjusted EBITDA&#x201D; section for a reconciliation of our net income to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	EBITDA and EBITDA to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	Adjusted EBITDA, both of which are
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	non-U.S. GAAP financial measure
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	s
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	. See also the information under the heading &#x201C;Adjusted EBITDA&#x201D; in the section &#x201C;How We Assess the Performance of Our Business&#x201D; for our definition of Adjusted EBITDA.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	We are pursuing several strategies to continue our profitable growth, including building brand awareness to continue customer acquisition, accelerating retail expansion, selectively broadening assortments in certain men&#x2019;s product categories and growing our women&#x2019;s business.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;">
	How We Assess the Performance of Our Business
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;COLOR:#000000;">
	In assessing the performance of our business, we consider a variety of financial and operating measures that affect our operating results.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 8PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	34
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<HR SIZE="3" STYLE="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
</HR>
<P STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<A NAME="eolPage36"></A>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#DLTH-20160131X10K_HTM_TOC">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Net Sales
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Net sales reflect our sale of merchandise plus shipping and handling revenue collected from our customers, less returns and discounts. Direct sales are recognized upon customer receipt of the product, while retail sales are recognized at the point of sale.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Comparable Store Sales
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Comparable store sales are generally calculated based upon retail stores that were open at least twelve full fiscal months as of the end of the reporting period. Our outlet stores are not included in the compa
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	rable store sales calculations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Comparable store sales allow us to evaluate how our retail store base
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	is per
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	forming by measuring the change
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in period over-period net sales in stores that have been open for twelve fis
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	cal months or more. Some of our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	competitors and other retailers calculate comparable store sales different
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ly than we do; as a result, our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	comparable store sales may not be comparable to similar data made available by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	other companies. While we have
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	experienced strong comparable store sales growth to date, we have excluded c
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	omparable stor
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	e sales data from this
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Annual Report on
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Form 10-K
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	due to the limited number of comparab
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	le retail stores as of January 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. Although
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	retail store
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	expansion is part of our growth strategy, we expect a significant percentage of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	our net sales to come from our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	direct segment for the foreseeable future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Gross Profit
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Gross profit is equal to our net sales
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	less cost of goods sold. Gross profit as a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	percentage of our net sales is
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	referred to as gross margin. Cost of goods sold includes the direct cost of p
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	urchased merchandise; inventory
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	shrinkage; inventory adjustments due to obsolescence, including excess and slo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	w-moving inventory and lower of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	cost or market reserves; inbound freight; and freight from our distribution ce
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	nters to our retail stores. The
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	primary drivers of the costs of individual goods are raw material costs. We expect
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	gross profit to increase to the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	extent that we successfully grow our net sales. Given the size of our direct segment
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	sales relative to our total net
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	sales, shipping and handling revenue has had a significant impact on our gross
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	profit and gross profit margin.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Historically, this revenue has partially offset shipping and handling expense included in selling, general and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	administrative expenses. Declines in shipping and handling revenues may have a
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	material adverse effect on our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	gross profit and gross profit margin, as well as Adjusted EBITDA to the ex
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	tent there are not commensurate
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	declines, or if there are increases, in our shipping and handling expense. Our gro
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ss profit may not be comparable
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to other retailers, as we do not include distribution network and store occupanc
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	y expenses in calculating gross
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	profit, but instead we include them in selling, general and administrative expenses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Selling, General and Administrative Expenses
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Selling
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, general and administrative expenses include all operating costs not
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	included in cost of goods sold.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	These expenses include all payroll and payroll-related expenses and occupancy exp
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	enses related to our stores and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to our operations at our headquarters, including utilities, depreciation and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	amortization
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and expenses of our distribution network
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. They also include
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	marketing expense, which primarily includes television advertising, catalo
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	g production, mailing and print
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	advertising costs, as well as all logistics costs associated with shipping product to our customers, consulting and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	software expenses and professional services fees. Selling, general and administrative expenses as a percentage of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	net sales is usually higher in lower-volume quarters and lower in higher-volume qu
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	arters because a portion of the
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	costs are relatively fixed
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our historical sales growth has been accompanied by increased selling, gener
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	al and administrative expenses.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	The most significant components of these increases are advertising, market
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ing and payroll costs. While we
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	expect these expenses to increase as we continue to open new stores, increa
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	se brand awareness and grow our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	organization to support our growing business, we believe these expenses will de
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	crease as a percentage of sales
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	over time.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Adjusted EBITDA
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We believe Adjusted EBITDA is a useful measure of operating performance, as it provides a clearer picture of operating results by excluding the effects of financing and investing activities by eliminating the effects of interest and depreciation costs and eliminating expenses that are not reflective of underlying business performance. We use Adjusted EBITDA to facilitate a comparison of our operating performance on a consistent basis from period-to-period and to provide for a more complete understanding of factors and trends affecting
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	our business.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We define Adjusted EBITDA as consolidated net income (loss) before depreciation and amortization, interest expense and provision for income taxes adjusted for the impact of certain items, including non-cash and other items we do not consider representative of our ongoing opera
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ting performance. We feel Adjusted EBITDA
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	is less susceptible to variances in actual performance resulting from depreciation,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	amortization and other items
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 8PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	35
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
	&nbsp;

</P>

<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">

	The unaudited pro forma net income information for all years presented gives effect to an adjustment for income tax expense on the income attributable to controlling interest as if we had been a &#x201C;C&#x201D; corporation at an assumed combined federal, state and local effective income tax rate, which approximate our statutory income tax rate, of 40%. No pro forma income tax expense was calculated on the income attributable to noncontrolling interest because this entity did not convert to &#x201C;C&#x201D; corporation.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Prior to November 25, 2015, we had been classified as an &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation for federal and state income tax purposes and therefore, we had not been subject to income taxes. Prior to tha
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	t date, our shareholders had
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	been subject to income tax on their distributive share of our earnings. In connection with our IPO, w
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	e converted to a &#x201C;C&#x201D; corporation.

	had been taxed as a &#x201C;C&#x201D; corporation at an estimated 40% effective tax rate, income taxes would have increased $2.1 million, or 21.7%, to $11.5 million in fiscal 2015 from $9.5 million in fiscal 2014.

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	Net income increased $3.8 million, or 16.0% to $27.4
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million in fiscal 2015 compared to $23.6 million in fiscal 2014, primarily due to the factors discussed above. Applying a pro forma 40% &#x201C;C&#x201D; corporation effective tax rate to both fiscal 2015 and fiscal 2014, rather than the &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation tax rate that actually applied to us prior to our IPO, pro forma net income increased $3.1 million, or 21.7%, to $17.3 million in fiscal 2015 from $14.2 million in fiscal 2014.
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<A HREF="#DLTH-20160131X10K_HTM_TOC">

</A>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Fiscal 2014 Compared to Fiscal 2013
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Net Sales
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Net sales increased $68.8 million, or 42.2%, to $231.9 million in fiscal 2014 compared to $163.1 million in fiscal 2013, driven by gains in both direct and retail segments of $56.0 million, or 36.6%, and $12.8 million, or 125.2%, respectively, across virtually all product categories. The direct net sales gains were largely attributable to our marketing efforts and increased catalog circulation, which resulted in greater e-commerce traffic to our website and sales through our call center. The $12.8 million increase in retail net sales was primarily attributable to the opening of two new stores during fiscal year 2014 coupled with full fiscal year sales related to our Bloomington store, which opened in October 2013. The two new stores contributed net sales of $7.3 million in fiscal 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Gross Profit
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Gross profit increased $39.0 million, or 42.4%, to $131.0 million in fiscal 2014 compared to $92.0 million in fiscal 2013. As a percentage of net sales, gross margin increased slightly to 56.5% of net sales in fiscal 2014 compared to 56.4% of net sales in fiscal 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Selling, Gene
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	ral and Administrative Expenses
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Selling, general and administrative expenses increased $31.2 million, or 41.1%, to $107.0 million in fiscal 2014 compared to $75.8 million in fiscal 2013. Selling, general and administrative expense
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	s as percentage of net sales were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	46.1% and 46.5% during fiscal 2014 and fiscal 2013, respectively. The increase in selling, general and administrative expenses of $31.2 million was primarily attributable to increases of $12.1 million in advertising and marketing costs, $10.3 million in selling expenses and $8.8 million in general and administrative expenses. The increase in selling expenses was consistent with the corresponding increase in net sales. The increase in general and administrative expenses was primarily due to an increase in personnel expenses and consulting services to support our growth. The increase in advertising and marketing costs was driven by an expansion of our national advertising campaign, coupled with an increase in catalog expenses primarily due to increased circulation. The increase in selling expenses was primarily driven by increased sales.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Interest Expense
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Interest expense increased $0.1 million to $0.3 million in fiscal 2014 compared to $0.2 million in fiscal 2013. The increase in interest expense was primarily due to a higher average balance drawn on the line of credit during fiscal 2014 as compared to fiscal 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Provision for Income Taxes
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Prior to November 25, 2015, we had been classified as an &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation for federal and state income tax purposes and therefore, we had not been subject to income taxes. Prior to tha
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	t date, our shareholders had
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	been subject to income tax on their distributive share of our earnings. In connection with our IPO, w
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	e converted to a &#x201C;C&#x201D; corporation.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	On a pro forma basis, if we had been taxed as a &#x201C;C&#x201D; corporation at an estimated 40% effective tax rate, income taxes would have increased $3.3 million, or 52.4%
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, to $9.5 million in fiscal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2014
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	from $6.2 million in fiscal
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Net Income
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Net income increased $8.1 million, or 52.4%, to $23.6 million in fiscal 2014 compared to $15.5 million in fiscal 2013, primarily due to the factors discussed above. Applying a pro forma 40% &#x201C;C&#x201D; corporation effective tax rate to both fiscal years, rather than the &#x201C;S&#x201D; corporation tax rate that actually applied to us, pro forma net income increased $4.9 million, or 52.4%, to $14.2 million in fiscal 2014 from $9.3 million in fiscal 2013.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 8PT">

</FONT>
</P>

	Reconciliation of Net Income to Adjusted EBITDA

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">

</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	non-GAAP financial measure

	s
</FONT>

	, for the periods indicated below. See the above section titled &#x201C;How We Assess the Performance of Our Business,&#x201D; for our definition of Adjusted EBITDA.

	sales

	in fiscal 2014.

	As a result of the factors discussed above in the &#x201C;Results of Operations&#x201D; section, Adjusted EBITDA increased $9.0 million, or 51.3%, to $26.7 million in fiscal 2014 compared to $17.6 million in fiscal 2013
</FONT>

	. As a percen

<EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
<A NAME="FIS_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Liquidity and Capital Resources
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	General
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Our business relies on cash from operating activities as well as cash on hand and a $40 million revolving line of credit as our primary sources of liquidity. Our
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	primary cash needs have been for inventory, payroll
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, store leases,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	capital
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	expenditures associated with opening new stores, infrastructure and information technol
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ogy
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. The most significant components o
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	f our working capital are cash,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	inventory, accounts payable and other current liabilities
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We expect to spend
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ap
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	proximately $24.0 million to $25
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.0 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	in
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	fiscal 2016 on capital expenditures, inclu
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ding a total of approximately $10
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.0 million to $11.0 million for new retail store expansion.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We expect it will take approximately $2.0 million to $2.6 million in capital expenditures and startin
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	g inventory to open a new store. At January 31, 2016
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, our working capital was
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	3
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	7
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, which includes cash of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$37.9 million
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	. Due to the seasonality of our business, a significant amount of cash from operating activities is generated during the fourth quarter of our fiscal year. During the first three quarters of our fiscal year, we typically are net users of cash in our operating activities as we acquire inventory in anticipation of our peak selling season, which occurs in the fourth quarter of our fiscal year. We also use cash in our investing activities for capital expenditures throughout all four quarters of our fiscal year. During the first three quarters of our fiscal year, we utili
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ze our revolving line of credit facility
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	to finance these cash requirements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	We believe that
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	our cash balance as of January 31, 2016,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	combined with
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	cash
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	flow from operating activities and
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the availability of cash under our revolving line of credit will be sufficient to cover working capital requirements and anticipated capital expenditures and for funding our growth strat
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	egy for the foreseeable future.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE="1">
</FONT>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="WIDTH:100%">
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 8PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-SIZE:8PT;">
	39
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 12PT">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Net Cash Provided by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Operating Activities
</FONT>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Operating activities
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	consist primarily of net income adjusted for non-cash items that include depreciation and amortization, loss on disposal of property, equipment and other assets, stock-based compensation and the effect of changes in assets and liabilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	For fiscal 2014, net cash provided by operating activities was $22.6 million, which consisted of net income of $24.1 million, non-cash depreciation and amortization of $1.8 million and other of $0.1 million, offset by cash used in operating assets and liabilities of $3.4 million. The cash used in operating assets and liabilities of $3.4 million primarily consisted of $11.8 million increase in inventory and prepaid expenses due to growth and opening of new stores, partially offset by $7.9 million increase in trade accounts payable and accrued expenses due to timing of payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	For
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	fiscal 2013, net cash provided by operating activities was $16.4 million, which consisted of net income of $16.1 million, non-cash depreciation and amortization of $1.2 million and other of $0.1 million, offset by cash used in operating assets and liabilities of $1.0 million. The cash used in operating assets and liabilities of $1.0 million primarily consisted of $8.6 million increase in inventory and prepaid expenses due to growth, partially offset by $7.5 million increase in trade accounts payable and accrued expense due to timing of payments.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Net Cash Used in Investing Activities
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Investing
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	activities consist primarily of capital expenditures for growth related to new store openings, information technology and enhancements for our distribution and corporate facilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	For
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	fiscal 2014, net cash used in investing activities was $7.1 million, primarily driven by capital expenditures of $5.3 million, due mainly to the opening of new corporate office facilities and two new stores, coupled with cash used of $1.8 million for the deconsolidation of Schlecht Enterprises, as discussed above.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	For fiscal 2013, net cash used in investing activities was $4.2 million, primarily driven by capital expenditures of $4.0 million for the opening of one new store, the acquisition of new corporate office facilities and technology related improvements at our existing corporate office facilities.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Net Cash Provided by
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	(Used in)
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Financing Activities
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	Financing activities consist primarily of borrowings and payments related to our revolving line of credit
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and other long-term debts
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, as well as distributions to
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	the individuals and entities that were
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	our shareholders
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	prior to our IPO
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	and holders of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	noncontrolling interest in variable interest entities and capital contributions to Schlecht Enterprises LLC and Schlecht Retail Ventures LLC.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:10PT 0PT 0PT;TEXT-INDENT:24.5PT;TEXT-ALIGN:LEFT;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE: 10PT">

	For fiscal 2015,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	ne
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	t cash provided by financing activities was $23.1 mil
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	lion, primarily consisting of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	$83
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	.
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	9
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	million in net proceeds
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	from our IPO
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	, which was consummated during the fourth quarter,
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	proceeds of $47.1 million from long term debt and $0.3 million for capital contributions to variable interest entities,

<FONT STYLE="DISPLAY: INLINE;">
	p

	artially offset by uses
